<HL>
   Campeau Units
   In U.S. Post Net
   In a Turnaround
   ----
   By Larry M. Greenberg
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
12/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE 30
</SO>
<CO>
   CMAFC T.CMP
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
</IN>
<LP>
   TORONTO -- Campeau Corp.'s two U.S. retailing
subsidiaries, Federated Department Stores Inc. and Allied
Stores Corp., reported combined net income of $3.9 million
for November, compared with a loss in the previous month.
   The monthly profit was the first by the two units since
they filed for Chapter 11 protection from creditors under the
federal Bankruptcy Code last January. Analysts said the
turnaround increases the chances the units could show a
profit for the fiscal fourth quarter ending Feb. 2. Campeau
is a real estate and retailing concern.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In a filing with the federal bankruptcy court in
Cincinnati, Federated reported net income of $1.7 million for
the four weeks ended Dec. 1 and Allied had earnings of $2.2
million. The results, which compared with a combined loss of
$23.7 million for the four weeks ended Nov. 3, don't include
costs related to the bankruptcy-law case. The companies
didn't disclose year-earlier figures.
   Revenue at both units were up from the previous month,
reflecting a pickup in sales in the pre-Christmas shopping
season. Federated's revenue rose 27% to $459 million from
$362 million. Allied had revenue of $275.4 million, up 49%
from $184.4 million.
   Still, the November revenues lagged behind year-earlier
levels, mainly because of a slowdown in consumer demand, the
companies said.
   "It is no secret that this year's Christmas selling season
was difficult for us, as it was for most retailers," said
Allen Questrom, chairman and chief executive officer of
Federated and Allied.
   But Mr. Questrom said he was encouraged by a continued
rise in gross profit margins at both units. He also said the
amount of cash available at Dec. 1, including investments,
unpurchased receivables and working capital facilities,
exceeded the expectations of the company and its bank
lenders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ901231-0148
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
901231-0148.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Economy:
   Leading Index
   Of Economy
   Declines 1.2%
   ---
   November Drop Was Fifth
   In a Row in New Signal
   Of Recessionary Trend
   ----
   By Paul Duke Jr.
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
12/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE 2
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
U.S. ECONOMIC INDICATORS (EMI)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The government's main economic forecasting
gauge declined for the fifth consecutive month in November,
in yet another sign that the economy is headed into a
recession.
   "The economy has been flattened by everyone's reaction to
world events," said Charles Renfro, chief economist with
Alphametrics, an economic forecasting concern in Bala Cynwyd,
Pa. Iraq's invasion of Kuwait appears to have sparked a
sudden downward spiral in consumer confidence, which is
rippling through the economy, although some analysts believe
the economy was weakening before the August invasion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The index of leading indicators -- a collection of
statistics intended to predict economic activity in the
months ahead -- dropped 1.2% in November after a revised
slide of 1.3% in October and a 0.8% fall in September, the
Commerce Department said. The October decline was reported
last month as 1.2%.
   Since World War II, the index has turned down, on average,
nine months before the beginning of a recession. But it
sometimes also has predicted recessions that didn't ensue. In
fact, the November decline marked the greatest number of
consecutive decreases since the index fell for six
consecutive months in mid-1984. No recession followed those
earlier signals.
   The index has been declining sporadically since the middle
of last year, with a brief show of strength early last
summer. Most economists now believe the economy is in a
recession -- generally defined as two consecutive quarters of
decline in output of goods and services -- but there is wide
disagreement about when it started and how deep and lengthy
it will be.
   Eight of the 11 components of the leading indicators
declined in November. The biggest negative factors were
falling manufacturers' orders for consumer goods, a decrease
in materials prices that respond quickly to supply and demand
(this component doesn't include oil prices), and an increase
in manufacturers' unfilled orders.
   The three gauges that indicated a positive trend were
rising stock prices, an increase in delays of deliveries of
supplies (which indicates increased demand), and a slight
rebound in the index of consumer expectations. The consumer
index, based on surveys, fell steeply from 79.3 in May to
50.9 in October. It rose last month to 52.8.
   The department's index of coincident indicators, which is
supposed to track the current pace of economic activity,
dropped 1.1% in November after an identical tumble in
October.
   ---
                   LEADING INDICATORS
                                                                                                       

   Here are the net contributions of the components of the
Commerce Department's index of leading indicators. After
various adjustments they produced a 1.3% decline in the index
for October and a 1.2% decline for November.
                                                                                                       

                                         Nov.    Oct.
                                         1990    1990
                                                                                                       

   Workweek ..........................   -.15    -.22
   Unemployment claims ...............   -.21    -.23
   Orders for consumer goods .........   -.34     .07
   Slower deliveries .................    .08    -.07
   Plant and equipment orders ........   -.23     .02
   Building permits ..................   -.05    -.21
   Durable order backlog .............   -.26     .03
   Materials prices ..................   -.30    -.14
   Stock prices ......................    .14    -.15
   Money supply ......................   -.13    -.19
   Consumer expectations .............    .07    -.29
                                                                                                       

   The seasonally adjusted index numbers (1982=100) for
November, and the change from October, are:
                                                                                                       

   Index of leading indicators ....... 139.7    -1.2
   Index of coincident indicators .... 130.3    -1.1
